TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of the Expansion of the Voting Franchise on the Size of Government
AU  - Husted, Thomas A.
AU  - Kenny, Lawrence W.
Y1  - 1997/02/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262065
DO  - 10.1086/262065
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 54
EP  - 82
VL  - 105
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines the claim that expansion of the voting franchise has been an important factor in the growth of government. State government spending and state and local spending are explained using a panel of 46 states for 1950-88. Elimination of poll taxes and literacy tests led to higher turnout, particularly among the poor, and a poorer pivotal voter. As predicted, we find that these changes, a fall in the income of voters relative to state income, and the ouster of Republicans from state government led to a sharp rise in welfare spending but no change in other spending.
AB  - This paper examines the claim that expansion of the voting franchise has been an important factor in the growth of government. State government spending and state and local spending are explained using a panel of 46 states for 1950-88. Elimination of poll taxes and literacy tests led to higher turnout, particularly among the poor, and a poorer pivotal voter. As predicted, we find that these changes, a fall in the income of voters relative to state income, and the ouster of Republicans from state government led to a sharp rise in welfare spending but no change in other spending.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262065
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262065
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Prices versus Quantities: The Political Perspective
AU  - Finkelshtain, Israel
AU  - Kislev, Yoav
Y1  - 1997/02/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262066
DO  - 10.1086/262066
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 83
EP  - 100
VL  - 105
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Regulation regimes subject to the influence of interest groups are compared. It is shown that the allocation of the regulated commodity varies with the implemented control and that the advantage of prices (vs. quotas) increases with the elasticity of the demand for or the supply of the commodity and decreases with the number of organized producers in the regulated industry. Control regimes can be ranked for negative, but not positive, externalities. Finally, a control regime leading to a more efficient commodity allocation also entails using fewer resources in rent-seeking activities.
AB  - Regulation regimes subject to the influence of interest groups are compared. It is shown that the allocation of the regulated commodity varies with the implemented control and that the advantage of prices (vs. quotas) increases with the elasticity of the demand for or the supply of the commodity and decreases with the number of organized producers in the regulated industry. Control regimes can be ranked for negative, but not positive, externalities. Finally, a control regime leading to a more efficient commodity allocation also entails using fewer resources in rent-seeking activities.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262066
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262066
Y2  - 2024/03/22
